Let’s first plot the mean utterance ratings before and after the exposure phase:

Statistical tests:

There seems to be a small numerical difference between the ratings of the cautious and the confident speaker. We can perform a t-test following the analysis of Yildirim et al. (2016), to determine whether this difference is significant.

print(summary(lm(auc_diff ~ speaker, data = aucs)))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = auc_diff ~ speaker, data = aucs)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -96.939  -8.233   1.313   8.687  38.336 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)       10.047      1.934   5.195 6.86e-07 ***
## speakercautious    1.106      2.735   0.404    0.687    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 16.52 on 144 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.001134,   Adjusted R-squared:  -0.005803 
## F-statistic: 0.1634 on 1 and 144 DF,  p-value: 0.6866

Both the plot and the t-test suggest, that the manipulation did not have an effect and that there is no significant difference between the ratings for the cautious and the confident speaker.
